    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today\u2019s slate with **Austin Riley** (73.16) and **James Wood** (71.27) serving as the focal points of the offensive attack. **Austin Riley** benefits from a high-floor matchup against Jake Irvin, where his dynamic platoon edge and prime spot in the heart of the order amplify his baseline projection. Meanwhile, **James Wood** is our most efficient play; leading off against Bryce Elder provides him with maximum plate appearance volume, and the park factor boost cements him as our premier outfield asset. **Tyler Soderstrom** also draws a strong 68.84 rating, as the soft matchup against Emerson Hancock provides a rare opportunity to exploit a pitcher with an xERA approaching 5.00, significantly buoying his efficiency despite his lower spot in the order.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was **Kyle Karros**, who finished at 44.69. While **Kyle Karros** benefits from a park boost and a favorable stolen base environment against a slower-to-deliver pitcher in Justin Wrobleski, his position at the bottom of the lineup and the presence of more established power-hitters like **Vinnie Pasquantino** and **Josh Naylor** ultimately pushed him out of the starting nine. We continue to monitor the status of **Corbin Carroll**, **Jazz Chisholm Jr.**, and **Jose Caballero**, who are all unavailable today due to team off-days. This leaves our stolen base targets thinner than desired; **Mickey Moniak** (48.33) remains in the lineup primarily for his ability to swipe a bag against a slow-moving pitcher, despite facing the stiff test of Justin Wrobleski\u2019s sub-3.00 xERA.\n\nRisks remain elevated across the board as the majority of our lineup is currently \"Lineup Pending.\" We are particularly wary of **Dalton Rushing**, whose efficiency (57.87) could crater if he is dropped further down the order or if the platoon disadvantage against Jose Quintana manifests in an early hook. Furthermore, while **Vinnie Pasquantino** shows promise, his matchup against Kyle Bradish is a significant bottleneck; the elite 2.63 xERA of the opposing starter forces us to rely heavily on wind assistance and the dynamic platoon split to keep his score near the 60-point threshold. We will adjust configurations if late lineup announcements force any of our core hitters into unfavorable defensive spots.",
